<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
Put a footnote number in your text to show when you are using another person&#8217;s ideas or words.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip; has been recently identified.<sup>1</sup>
</blockquote>
<br>
This number directs your reader to a footnote at the bottom of your page. The footnote contains detailed information about the work you are citing.
<br><br>
<strong>FOOTNOTES</strong>
<br><br>
In the footnote, first give the full details of the original source, followed by 
<strong>quoted in</strong>, and then give the full details of the secondary source that you consulted.
<br>
<blockquote class="footnotes ref-indent-1-27cm">
	<span class="smaller">
		1. Janet Jones, &#34;Corporate Identity Theory,&#34; 
		<em>Journal of Management Philosophy</em> 10, no. 2 (2025): 155, quoted in Andrew Smith, &#34;Teaming with Wildlife: Promoting Team Development through Volunteer Service at Auckland Zoo,&#34; <em>New Zealand Business Review</em> 17 (2050): 7.
	</span>
</blockquote>
